\subsection lin_calls Calls format
Two versions exist for most of the API calls:
 -# Static calls embed the name of the signal or interface in the name of the call (e.g. *l_u8 l_u8_rd_sss (void)*)
 -# Dynamic calls provide the signal or interface as a parameter (e.g. *l_u8 l_u8_rd (l_signal_handle sss)*)

The static API calls are implemented as much as possible.
\note Dynamic calls are required for Node Configuration API

The name of interface for static calls:
 -# Slave - "sl1"
 -# Master - "ma1"

The name of interface for dynamic calls specified by enumeration ::l_ifc_handle.

\subsection lin_calls_diff API interface differences from the Standard
The l_u8 ld_read_by_id_callout (l_ifc_handle iii, l_u8 id, l_u8* pci, l_u8* data) has additinal parameter "pci" to specify variable "data" length plus one.

\subsection lin_interact Interaction with LDF-dependent LIN API

\subsubsection lin_signals Signals interaction functions
The functions to interact with Signals has names as specified in the Standard, where "sss" - is Signal name from LDF-file.

\subsubsection lin_flags Flags interaction functions
Flags are local objects in a node and they are used to synchronise the application program with the LIN core.
The flags will be automatically set by the LIN core and can only be tested or cleared by the application program.
Flags may be attached to all types of frames. A flag is set when the frame/signal is considered to be transmitted
respectively received.

In Melexis implementation of Standard LIN API two types of flags are created:
-# A flag that is attached to a Signal
-# A flag that is attached to a Frame

The function prototypes to interact with flags are specified by Standard:
 -# *l_bool l_flg_tst_fff (void)* - Returns the current state of the flag specified by the name *fff*: returns zero if the flag is cleared, non-zero otherwise
 -# *void l_flg_clr_fff (void)* - Sets the current value of the flag specified by the name *fff* to zero

The flag name "fff" is implementation specific. In current implementation, Flag name consists of Signal/Frame name plus prefix "s_"
for Signal and "f_" for Flag. For example, test flag function *l_bool l_flg_tst_s_engineTemp (void)* will be generated for
Signal - "engineTemp".

In the case both Master and Slave APIs are generated for the same device then the Flag name "fff" also includes the interface as additional prefix:
"sl1_" for Slave Flags and "ma1_" for Master Flags.

Find \ref lin_signals.h "lin_signals.h" for full list of generated functions for interaction with Signals and Flags based on LDF-file.
*/
